Title: Vegetables
Bio: Vegetables are the food group that people resort to when they want to say 'I eat these to be healthy.' They typically are not complete proteins and are usually the side dish. Not everything here is a botanical vegitable. Mainly made up water, dont contribute much calorically, provide a wide array of vitamins, minerals and plant compounds. Vegetables are generally healthy so anything above F could very well be in a proper meal plan so dont take a lower rating as too descriminating. The top tier is saved for super foods. Note the different ways that vegetables arfreshness can impact the nutrition and healthiness of the vegetable, so be wary of the different nutrtional benefits.

Artichoke.name: Artichoke
Artichoke.Bio:
- B Tier
- Best source of Fiber: Regulates Digestive System
- Inulin - Acts as a Prebiotic
- Shwon to increase production of Bile: removes toxic waste and breaks down fats
- Among the best sources of antioxidants: Vitamin-C, Flavonoids, and Phenolic  Compounds:
  fight against free radicals and certain cancers
- Shown to raise HDL levels
- Shown to regulate Blood Pressure
- Shown to ease symptoms IBS
- May lead to gas and upset stomach and diarrhea
- When cooked loses several of the nutrients as Vitamins like Vitamin-C as they are heat sensitive.

Carrot.name: Carrot
Carrot.Bio:
- Top Tier 
- Best source of Carotenoids (where term carotenoids come from)
    - Alpha Carotene and Beta Carotene: Convert into vit. A: preserves eye health and protects against free radicals
    - Shown to reduce risk of cancer
    - Shown to manage bllod pressure levels
- May enflare pollen related allergies
- Shown to be generally more nutritious and easier to digest cooked.

Dill_Pickle.name: Dill_Pickle
Dill_Pickle.Bio:
- C Tier
- Vitamin K: Blood clotting and bone building
- Sodium from brining process
- Shown to aid in rehydration and restoring electrolyte balance
- Shown to combat insulin resistance and inflammation
- Acetic Acid: Shwon to help with Muscle Cramps
- Probiotics: Promote gut health

Chili_Pepper.name: Chili_Pepper
Chili_Pepper.Bio:
- Top Tier
- One of the best sources of Vit. C that combats damage caused by free radicals
- Vit. B6 for healthy nervoius and immune system
- Among the highest in antioxidants:
    - Capsaicin: Strong anti-inflammatory shown to promote heart health also where spice comes in
    - Lutein: preserves eye health
    - Sinapic Acid
    - Ferulic Acid
    - Shown to boost Metabolism
- Chili Peppers are a nightshade meaning some people with health conditions cannot have them
- More nutritious raw: preserves nutrients (i.e Vit. C)

Bell_Pepper.name: Bell_Pepper
Bell_Pepper.Bio:
- A Tier
- Good source of Vitamin C, for fighting against free radicals
- Beta-Carotene: Converted into Vitamin A: mainly for eye health
- Capsanthin: Promotes Eye Health
- Quercetin: Protects against chronic diseases
- Diuretic: Flushes out excess fluid
- Nightshade: Best for people with certain Inflammatory and autoimmune diseases to avoid
- Can be eaten both raw and cooked but more nutritious if eaten raw as nutrients heat sensitive

Celery.name: Celery
Celery.Bio:
- C Tier
- Good source of antioxidants: Vit. C, A and some flavonoids
- Shown to reduce inflammation
- Shown to promote digestive health
- Diuretic
- Not as good nutritionally but almost 'designed' to be for weight loss

Watercress.name: Watercress
Watercress.Bio:
- A Tier
- Vitamin-K: Blood clotting and bone building
- Highest concentration of antioxidants: Beta-Cartene, Lutein, Zeaxanthin, Vit. C and variety of Flavonoids.
- Sulforaphane: antioxidant anti-inflammatory
- Isothicyantes: anti-cancer effects
- May worsen preexisting thyroids conditions

Onion.name: Onion
Onion.Bio:
- A Tier
- Antioxidants: Quercetin (Flavonoid) Anti-Inflammatory, Shown to control blood sugar
- Allicin: Strong Antimicrobial Properties
- Onionin A - Sulfur Compound: Combats Cancer, Regulates White blood cell activity
- Shown to Fortify Bones
- Diuretic: Flush Out Excess Fluid
- May Aggravate Irritable Bowel Syndrome
- Better Raw: Sulfur Compounds
- Look past Macro and Micros for this one

Asparagus.name: Asparagus
Asparagus.Bio:
- A Tier
- Best source of Folate: Helps form Red Blood Cells, DNA and RNA
- Solid sources of Antioxidants: Vit. C and E and Flavonoids
- Quercetin and Kaempferol: Lower Blood Pressure and has Anti-Inflammatory and 
    Antiviral Properties
- Protodioscin: Restores Vitality, Libido and reduces negative effects of stress
- Shown to support Ovarian Health
- Diuretic: Flush Excess Fluid and Salf from Body
- Eaiser to Digest when cooked (perferable)

Arugula.name: Arugula
Arugula.Bio:
- A Tier
- Great source of Vitamin-K used for Blood Clotting and Bone Building
- Good Source of:
    - Beta Carotene: Converted in Vit. A
    - Lutein: Antioxidant, preserves Eye Health
    - Zeaxanthin: Antioxidant, fights free radicals
    - Calcium: For bones and teeth
    - Magnesium: Muscle and nerve system regulation
- Contains Glucosinolates: Combats imflammation and has antimicrobial properties

Green_Cabbage.name: Green_Cabbage
Green_Cabbage.Bio:
- B Tier
- Good source of vitamin K
- Good source of vitamin C
- Another cruciferous vegetable thus being high in
- Quercetin: regulates BP levels
- Kaempferol: protects against chronic disease
- Glucosinolates: anti-inflammatory
- Indole-3-Cabrinol
- Shown to improve heart and digestive health
- May make preexisting thyroid issues worse

Brussel_Sprout.name: Brussel_Sprout
Brussel_Sprout.Bio:
- A Tier
- Omega 3 Fatty Acids: ALAs less useful than kind in animal sources
- Cruciferous vegetables usually have the following as well:
- Quercetin: Regulates Blood Pressure Levels
- Kaempferol: Protects against chronic diseases
- Sulforaphane: Antioxidant and Anti-Inflammatory
- Indole-3-Carbinol: Stimulates Detoxification
- Choline: Brain and memory development
- May worsen preexisting thyroid issues
- Raw is more nutritient dense but not by much

Water_Chestnut.name: Water_Chestnut
Water_Chestnut.Bio:
- B Tier
- Best source of copper: helps make red blood cells, keeps healthy immune system, and aids in iron absorption
- Good source of potassium for normal fluid levels
- Vitamin B2: Convering carbs into fuel.
- Antioxidants: Catechin and Ferulic Acid: strong anti cancer properties
- Shwon to regulate blood pressure.

Cauliflower.name: Cauliflower
Cauliflower.Bio:
- B Tier
- Best source of choline: brain and memory development
- Vitamin C: Antioxidant
- Sulforaphane: Antioxidant, anti-inflammatory
- Indole-3-Carbinol: Stimulates Detoxification
- May enhance preexisting thyroid issues
- Raw: More Antioxidant content
- Cooked: More Indole Content

Green_Bean.name: Green_Bean
Green_Bean.Bio:
- C Tier
- Vitamin-K: Blood Clotting, Bone Building
- Antioxidants: Beta Carotene, Lutein, Vit. C and Flavonoids like Quercetin and Kaempferol
- Shown to Improve Digestive, Bone and Heart Health
- Antinutrients: Phytic Acid and Lectins, reduced by cooking

Kale.name: Kale
Kale.Bio:
- Tier
- Best source of Vitamin K: used for blood clotting and bone building
- Carotenoids: Beta-Carotene, Lutein, Zeaxanthin: Preserves Eye Health
- Antioxidants
- Sulforaphane- Antioxidants and anti-inflamatory
- Indole-3-Carbinol: Stimulates Detoxification
- More Nutrient Dense Raw: Vitamin-C is heat sensitive
- May worsen Pre-existening thyroid conditions especially eaten raw
- People who take Blood thinners should be wary due to high vitamin K.

Potato.name: Potato
Potato.Bio:
- B Tier
- Good starchy carbohydrate
- Resisant starch: good for gut bacteria and regulating blood sugar
- Antioxidants: Vit. C (protects against free radicals), Catechin (relieves 
oxidative stress), Chlorogenic Acid (regulates blood sugar)
- Boosting Insulin Sensitivity
- Shown to improve digestive health
- Shown to aid in muscle and nerve function
- Nightshade
- Often prepared in unhealthy ways

Corn.name: Corn
Corn.Bio:
- C Tier
- Good source of Vit. B1 ot help generate energy from nutrients
- Good source of antioxidants like: Vit. C, ferulic acid, lutein, and zeaxanthin
- Phytic acid and Lectins: antinutrients that impair nutrient absorption
- Commonly GMO
- Raw: More nutrient dense
- Cooked: Lower antinutrient content

Cucumber.name: Cucumber
Cucumber.Bio:
- C Tier
- Mostly made of water 95%
- Used to Fend off dehydration
- Shown to combat chronic diseases
- Have a strong Anti-Inflammatory effect
- Support Regular Bowel Movement
- Diuretic: Flush out excess fluids in the body

Collard_Greens.name: Collard_Greens
Collard_Greens.Bio:
- Top Tier
- Among the best sources of Vit. K for bone building and blood clots
- Manganese which helps the formation of bones, connective tissue, and certain hormones
- Calcium: maintining healthy bones and teeth
- Beta Carotene, Lutein and Zeaxanthin
- Sulforaphane: antioxidant, anti-inflammatory
- Indole-3-Carbinal: Stimulates detoxification
- May inflame preexisting thyroid issues
- Cooked: More Carotenoids
- Raw: More vitamin C

Jalapenos.name: Jalapenos
Jalapenos.Bio:
- A Tier
- Vitamin B6: Upkeep of immune and nervous system
- Antioxidants: Vitamin C
- Capsaicin: Anti-inflammatory, heart health
- Lutein and Zeaxanthin: Eye Preservation
- Shown to boost metabolism
- Shown to combat certain cancers
- May cause GI issues in excess
- Nightshade

Eggplant.name: Eggplant
Eggplant.Bio:
- D Tier
- Eggplant has lowest micronutrient content per gram
- Very rich in Anthocyanins:
    - Nasunin: Prects Brain Cell Membranes
- Shown to regulate blood sugar levels
- Shown to Benefit Heart Health
- Nightshade: People with inflammatory or autoimmune diesases should be wary
- Contain Antinutrients: Tannins, Oxalates, Phytic Acid
- Cooking does reduce antinutrient content

Spinach.name: Spinach
Spinach.Bio:
- Top Tier
- Best souce of:
- Folate: used in production of DNA and RNA
- Magnesium: regulates muscle and nerve function and aids in protein bone, and DNA synthesis
- Iron: Hemoglobin and Myoglobin Creation: transfer oxygen throughout the body
- Vitamin-B2: Converts Carbohydrates to fuel
- One of the best sources of:
- Vitamin K: Blood clotting and bone building
- Manganese: Formation of bones, hormones
- Calcium: Strengthens bones and teeth
- Antioxidants: Beta-Carotene, Lutein, Zeaxanthin, Vit. C, Quercetin, Kaempferol
- Shown to regulate blood pressure levels
- Very High in Oxalates: Antinutrients that bind to Calcium and may lead to kidney stones in excess.
- Better Cooked: Reduces Oxalate content, allows for better absorption of calcium and iron
- Loses out on antioxidant content when cooked
- Iron better absorbed when paired with foods higher in Vitamin C, Copper and Citric Acid.

Beetroot.name: Beetroot
Beetroot.Bio:
- A Tier
- Highest in sugars (8g per 100g) but this isnt like eating 8 grams of junk food
- High in Nitrates: Improves Cardiovascular and Cognitive Function
- Linked with increased V0_2 output
- Shown to aid in post workout recovery
- Betaine: involved in Liver functiona and cellular reproduction
- Shown to support brain and digestive health
- Higher in Oxalates (antinutrient): interferes with calcium absorption
- Fructans: may give people with IBS issues
- Cooking Beats redices antinutrient content while minimally affecting vitamins

Okra.name: Okra
Okra.Bio:
- D Tier
- Vitamin K: Blood Clotting and Bone Building
- Vitamin C: Protects against free radicals
- Mucilage: Thick, Gel-like substance that binds to Cholesterol, Causing it to 
be Excreted (effective causing it to lower Cholesterol levels)
- Contains Solanine: Toxic compound that in excess may lead to joint pain.
- Contains Antinutrients: oxalates and Lectins
- Cooked: Lower Antinutrient concentration
- Raw: more nutritious

Radish.name: Radish
Radish.Bio:
- B Tier
- Solid source of Antioxidants: Vitamin-C and Phenolic Compounds
- Natural antifungal
- Shown to support healthy digestion
- Shown to help liver detoxify
- Shown to help the kidney flush out toxins

Turnip.name: Turnip
Turnip.Bio:
- D Tier
- Antioxidants: Vitamin C, Glucosinolates, and anthocyanins.
- Shown to have anti-cancer and antibacterial properties
- Shown to regulate blood sugar.
- May interfere with Thyroid gland.
- Nothing wrong with them but they dont really help too much for a vegetable

Broccoli.name: Broccoli
Broccoli.Bio:
- Top Tier
- Good source of Vitamin K for bone building and blood clotting
- Good source of Vitamin C for antioxidants fighting free radicals
- Good source of Lutein and Zeaxanthin: Antioxidants that perserve eye health
- Quercetin: Manages blood pressure levels
- Kaempferol: Protects against inflammattion and chronic diseases
- Contains Glucosinolates (Sulforaphane): Antioxidant, Anti-Inflammatory
- Indole-3-Carbinol: Shown to stimulate detoxifying enzymes in gut and liver
- Choline: Brain and Memory development
- May cause thyroid issues but is helped by cooking
- Cooking provides more vitamin K and Carotenoids but less vitamin C

Sweet_Potato.name: Sweet_Potato
Sweet_Potato.Bio:
- Top Tier
- Healthier Starchy Carbohydrate source
- Best source of Beta Carotene:
- Converted into Vitamin-A: Protects eye health, immune health and healthy skin
- Contains Vitamin C and Chlorogenic Acid: shown to regulate blood sugar levels
- Resistant starch: Beneficial for gut bacteria
- Higher in Oxalates which is reduced by boiling.

Iceberg_Lettuce.name: Iceberg_Lettuce
Iceberg_Lettuce.Bio:
- D Tier
- 96% water
- Vitamin K and Carotenoids
- Just to fill no nutritional value

Parsnip.name: Parsnip
Parsnip.Bio:
- B Tier
- Vitamin C protects against free radicals
- Quercetin, Kaemperfol, Apigenin: Enhance immunity and protects against infections
- Fiber Helps moves food through GI tract
- Shown to promote heart health
- More nutrituous raw

Bok_Choy.name: Bok_Choy
Bok_Choy.Bio:
- B Tier
- Good source of Vitamin C: Antioxidant
- Vitamin K for blood clotting and bone building
- Beta-Carotene -> Vitamin-A
- Sulphorophane: activates antioxidants and anti-inflamatory effects
- Shown to promote heart health
- Has Anti-cancer properties
- Raw may hinder thyroid function in those with preexisting issues
- Raw Bok Choy More nutritionally dense

Endive.name: Endive
Endive.Bio:
- B Tier
- Vit. K: bone building and blood clotting
- Folate: helps for DNA and RNA and used in protein metabolism
- Has antioxidants: Beta Carotene, Querceting, Myricetin, and Kaempferol

Peas.name: Peas
Peas.Bio:
- B Tier
- Good source of plant protein: over 5g per 100g
- Higher in sugar: 6g per 100g
- Best source of Bit B1: Helps the body generate energy from nutrients
- Fiber: Aids in Digestive process
- Antioxidants: Vitamin-C, Lutein, Zeaxanthin, and various Polyphenols
- Antinutrients: Lectens, Phyic Acid and Tannins but are reduced through cooking.

Garlic.name: Garlic
Garlic.Bio:
- Top Tier
- Manganese: Contributes to the formation of bones, connective tissue and certain hormones
- Vit. B6: Maintains nervous and immune systems.
- Selenium: Acts like an Antioxidant
- Calcium: Strengthens Bones and teeth
- Copper: Aids in iron absorption
- Contains Sulfur compounds:
- Allicin: shown to prevent certain cancers and manage blood sugar, cholesterol, and blood pressure
- Diallyl Disulfide and S-Allyl Cysteine: Antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial and cardiovascular protective benefits
- Reduces risk of alzheimers and dementia
- In Excess causes gastrointestinal issues but it takes a lot.

Mustard_Green.name: Mustard_Green
Mustard_Green.Bio:
- Top Tier
- Vitamin K: Blood Clotting and Bone Building
- Carotenoids: Beta-Carotene, Lutein, Zeaxanthin
- Vitamin C: Protects against free radicals
- Sulforaphaene: Antioxidant, Anti-inflammatory
- Indole-3-Carbinol: Stimulates Detoxification
- Worsens Preexistening Thyroid Conditions
- Much More nutritious Raw

Romaine_Lettuce.name: Romaine_Lettuce
Romaine_Lettuce.Bio:
- A Tier
- Carotenoids: Beta Carotene & Lutein: Preserves Eye Health
- Antioxidants: Vit. C, Flavonoids, Tocopherols
- Folate: Helps form DNA & RNA

Leek.name: Leek
Leek.Bio:
- C Tier
- Kaemferol: Protects against Chronic Diseases
- Lutein & Zeaxanthin- Eye Health, Preservation
- Allicin: Antimicrobial, Manages Cholesterol
- Shown to promote brain and digestive function
- Oxalates may lead to Kidney Stones in Excess, reduced by cooking
- More Nutritious Raw
